So the normal cells, neurons in this case, like to hang out with themselves.

238
00:14:33.954 --> 00:14:37.734
Immune cells like to be close to blood vessels.

239
00:14:37.814 --> 00:14:40.674
They like to cluster around endothelial cells.

240
00:14:40.754 --> 00:14:44.374
And the neuroepithelial-like, so this very early stem cell-like

241
00:14:44.494 --> 00:14:48.284
state, seems to cluster with all the other cell states present in

242
00:14:48.314 --> 00:14:48.874
those tumors.

243
00:14:51.103 --> 00:14:54.684
And now I'll show you the last part that I'm very excited about to really ask, what

244
00:14:54.694 --> 00:14:56.314
does it even mean, these cell states?

245
00:14:56.704 --> 00:15:00.294
Are they a mere reflection of distance from a blood vessel,

246
00:15:00.394 --> 00:15:04.254
distance from hypoxic mesenchymal, or do they truly have a

247
00:15:04.314 --> 00:15:06.134
different function within these tumors?

248
00:15:06.354 --> 00:15:10.314
Because making these cell states comes at a cost, so what does the

249
00:15:10.334 --> 00:15:11.174
tumor get out of it?

250
00:15:12.334 --> 00:15:15.834
In order to address this question, we of course, couldn't do that in patient

251
00:15:15.894 --> 00:15:19.654
samples and needed models from these patients, grew them in multiple

252
00:15:19.974 --> 00:15:20.814
different ways,

253
00:15:21.814 --> 00:15:25.634
namely as neurospheres in non-serum stem cell media, or

254
00:15:25.714 --> 00:15:29.374
adherent on laminin, or in co-culture with normal

255
00:15:29.474 --> 00:15:33.174
human or rat astrocytes and neurons, or as PDX.

256
00:15:33.634 --> 00:15:36.574
And then always projected these single-cell

257
00:15:37.294 --> 00:15:41.214
profiles back on our patient cohort to ask, to what degree do

258
00:15:41.254 --> 00:15:43.444
our cultures reflect what we actually see in patients?

259
00:15:44.194 --> 00:15:48.154
And that's shown over down at the bottom, a little bit busy also, but I wanted to

260
00:15:48.194 --> 00:15:51.954
appreciate that the orange dots, those are the cells coming

261
00:15:52.234 --> 00:15:56.064
from cultures that were either grown as a PDX or co-cultures,

262
00:15:56.514 --> 00:15:59.734
were the only ones that went all the way down this hierarchy that I had shown you

263
00:15:59.774 --> 00:16:02.054
before, a trajectory of differentiation.

264
00:16:02.554 --> 00:16:06.384
So if you want to see ependymal and neuronal differentiation of these tumor

265
00:16:06.414 --> 00:16:08.814
cells, you cannot just grow the tumor cells alone.

266
00:16:09.254 --> 00:16:12.594
If you grow them alone, then you enrich for the stem cell-like state, which makes

267
00:16:12.654 --> 00:16:16.094
sense. That's what we enrich for. But if you want to see differentiation, you need

268
00:16:16.134 --> 00:16:19.573
more sophisticated ways to grow them.

269
00:16:19.954 --> 00:16:23.764
And so we used those two PDX and co-cultures grown, as I said,

270
00:16:23.814 --> 00:16:27.514
either with rat or human neurons and astrocytes, labeled the tumor cells in

271
00:16:27.554 --> 00:16:27.894
red,

272
00:16:28.894 --> 00:16:32.754
and then in the in vivo system, used two-photon imaging together with Varun

273
00:16:32.774 --> 00:16:36.474
Venkataraman in Heidelberg with a cranial window to ask,

274
00:16:36.794 --> 00:16:38.614
when you follow these cells over time,

275
00:16:39.654 --> 00:16:41.894
can you determine different morphologies?

276
00:16:42.454 --> 00:16:45.934
With the end goal then of projecting that back onto the cell states I had described

277
00:16:45.944 --> 00:16:49.694
earlier. And indeed, both in the PDX in vivo

278
00:16:49.704 --> 00:16:53.474
as well as in these co-cultures in vitro, we saw four

279
00:16:53.514 --> 00:16:56.454
different morphologies in the time that we observed the tumor.

280
00:16:57.194 --> 00:17:00.994
We saw either naked cells that we called having zero tumor

281
00:17:01.034 --> 00:17:04.884
microtubules on the left, then cells with one to three short tumor

282
00:17:04.954 --> 00:17:05.644
microtubules,

283
00:17:06.504 --> 00:17:10.244
cells that had many, but certainly more than three short tumor microtubules,

284
00:17:10.854 --> 00:17:14.454
and then cells that had one to three very long projections

285
00:17:14.854 --> 00:17:18.835
over on the very right. And again, this is shown in vitro as well as in vivo.

286
00:17:21.075 --> 00:17:24.654
As a first step to ask which of the cell states they could be

287
00:17:24.734 --> 00:17:28.634
reflecting then, we did immunofluorescence stainings on these mice and on

288
00:17:28.674 --> 00:17:29.794
these cultures after

289
00:17:30.614 --> 00:17:32.314
in vivo imaging or in vitro imaging,

290
00:17:33.134 --> 00:17:37.054
and saw that indeed the naked cells, the zero TMs and the short TM

291
00:17:37.094 --> 00:17:39.374
cells, were positive for stem cell markers.

292
00:17:39.434 --> 00:17:41.754
So we thought they could be neuroepithelial-like

293
00:17:42.694 --> 00:17:46.614
tumor cells. Whereas the cell that had the many projections, and I'll show

294
00:17:46.674 --> 00:17:47.894
you a video of them in a little bit,

295
00:17:49.014 --> 00:17:52.834
had early expression of CCDC40, which is an

296
00:17:52.874 --> 00:17:56.794
early ependymal marker. It was the only cell that had this

297
00:17:57.034 --> 00:18:00.794
marker present. And then these long projection tumor cells

298
00:18:01.454 --> 00:18:04.034
had a few markers of early neuronal development present.

299
00:18:04.074 --> 00:18:07.994
So we thought this could be the neuronal-like cells.But I wanted

300
00:18:08.014 --> 00:18:11.114
to look a little bit more into detail, having the spatial technology in the lab.

301
00:18:11.634 --> 00:18:14.954
So we grew tumor cells labeled here again in red on the

302
00:18:15.594 --> 00:18:18.854
Xenium slide with co-cultures, with normal human neurons.

303
00:18:19.134 --> 00:18:22.914
Those are IPC derived. And then applied the Xenium technology

304
00:18:23.014 --> 00:18:24.774
spatial transcriptomics on the slide.

305
00:18:25.454 --> 00:18:28.994
And you can do this beautifully because then in the end, you can determine who is a

306
00:18:29.014 --> 00:18:31.874
tumor cell or not by overlaying the IF profile as shown here.

307
00:18:32.314 --> 00:18:34.174
So all the red cells are tumor cells.

308
00:18:34.614 --> 00:18:37.374
You can see that a lot of the normal cells, the normal neurons, are in the

309
00:18:37.394 --> 00:18:40.624
background, of course, not lighting up in red, but still having the same

310
00:18:40.654 --> 00:18:44.114
transcripts present. And then you can even do subcellular

311
00:18:44.154 --> 00:18:48.094
localization of transcripts and look at transcripts present in the soma

312
00:18:48.114 --> 00:18:50.854
in this case, and at the protection of this tumor cell.

313
00:18:51.294 --> 00:18:55.054
And indeed, those transcripts that were present were the ones that helped us

314
00:18:55.074 --> 00:18:56.874
define the neuronal-like

315
00:18:57.714 --> 00:18:59.594
cell state in supratentorial ependymoma.

316
00:19:00.254 --> 00:19:04.014
So what I had shown you in the slide before with IF, we could indeed

317
00:19:04.234 --> 00:19:06.834
confirm here, and this was the case for all the different cell states

318
00:19:07.794 --> 00:19:08.354
I had shown you.

319
00:19:09.974 --> 00:19:13.464
And then most beautifully, we can follow them over time and see how they

320
00:19:13.794 --> 00:19:16.414
move and behave in the in vivo context.

321
00:19:17.114 --> 00:19:20.894
And this is what these neuroepithelial-like tumor cells do in the

322
00:19:20.934 --> 00:19:24.654
brain and in vitro co-cultures. They either don't move or they move very

323
00:19:24.794 --> 00:19:28.034
slowly in a linear fashion over time,

324
00:19:29.614 --> 00:19:33.034
whereas the neuronal-like tumor cells have this saltatory

325
00:19:33.174 --> 00:19:37.094
behavior, which is reminiscent of early neurons in the developing human cortex,

326
00:19:37.534 --> 00:19:40.994
which means that a projection goes first and then the cell nucleus is dragged

327
00:19:41.034 --> 00:19:44.474
behind in a jumping fashion. That's how early radial glia cells

328
00:19:44.914 --> 00:19:47.714
jump when they grow to the external layers of the cortex.

329
00:19:49.014 --> 00:19:52.854
And then this is this ependymoma-like glia cell that I showed you before earlier.

330
00:19:52.894 --> 00:19:56.764
These guys never moved. They were stationary and just extended and retracted their

331
00:19:56.814 --> 00:19:57.974
many fibers over time.

332
00:20:00.074 --> 00:20:03.974
Looking more at these neuronal-like cancer cells, they really truly mimic immature

333
00:20:04.274 --> 00:20:08.094
neurons in multiple ways, not just with the saltatory behavior, but

334
00:20:08.174 --> 00:20:11.874
also with branching. You can see here one of the tumor cells that spans many

335
00:20:11.934 --> 00:20:15.574
hundred microns, extending through the brain of the mouse.

336
00:20:16.383 --> 00:20:20.334
They also have these protrusions that we know are from early neuronal development,

337
00:20:20.834 --> 00:20:24.464
where the goal in normal development is to look for nutrients or gradients that

338
00:20:24.494 --> 00:20:25.934
they then follow for their development,

339
00:20:26.854 --> 00:20:30.334
and also retraction, which is a phenomenon again seen in normal development.

340
00:20:30.674 --> 00:20:32.854
When they don't find what they're looking for, they retract their

341
00:20:32.874 --> 00:20:35.994
projections. We measured this

342
00:20:36.934 --> 00:20:40.894
migration speed, as well as the migratory patterns and proliferation shown

343
00:20:40.974 --> 00:20:44.754
summarized on this slide. And again, this is just showing you more

344
00:20:44.994 --> 00:20:48.354
quantified that the neuronal-like cancer cells are really the ones

345
00:20:49.074 --> 00:20:50.454
that migrate the fastest.

346
00:20:51.414 --> 00:20:54.274
They are the ones that have also very special migratory patterns, like the

347
00:20:54.294 --> 00:20:58.054
