00:27:52.478 --> 00:27:56.438
postdoctoral fellows in my lab. And this paper is coming

481
00:27:56.498 --> 00:28:00.158
out along with Mariela's and Steve Mack's paper in "Nature," along with Michael

482
00:28:00.178 --> 00:28:00.618
Taylor's

483
00:28:01.578 --> 00:28:05.018
really beautiful PFA ependymoma in males androgen therapy.

484
00:28:06.138 --> 00:28:09.678
So I also wanted to acknowledge various collaborators and founding

485
00:28:10.758 --> 00:28:14.718
institutions, including Mariela and Michael and Richard, who gave us some of

486
00:28:14.758 --> 00:28:18.218
the early tools to actually do this, and then various other collaborators at the

487
00:28:18.238 --> 00:28:20.338
University of Michigan who made this work possible.

488
00:28:21.658 --> 00:28:25.558
So I wanted to start with what Mariela just showed you, but stepping back a little

489
00:28:25.598 --> 00:28:29.178
bit. So at the two ends of the spectrum of brain tumors, in

490
00:28:29.238 --> 00:28:32.958
children, you see a lot of epigenetic deregulation, and this goes on the

491
00:28:33.018 --> 00:28:36.538
concept that these tumors mirror developmental

492
00:28:37.538 --> 00:28:41.118
abnormalities that Michael and Richard have talked about for a long time.

493
00:28:41.438 --> 00:28:45.178
And at the other end of the spectrum are glioblastomas that have these very

494
00:28:45.218 --> 00:28:48.918
traditional genetic alterations such as EGFR or

495
00:28:48.958 --> 00:28:50.888
PTEN deletion or cell cycle regulators.

496
00:28:51.278 --> 00:28:55.098
And I want to draw your attention to this middle group that happens in

497
00:28:55.198 --> 00:28:58.778
young adults and during early adulthood, is the IDH mutations.

498
00:28:59.138 --> 00:29:02.678
So these mutations are in isocitrate dehydrogenase 1, and these

499
00:29:02.718 --> 00:29:06.248
introduce a paradigm of how metabolites can actually change

500
00:29:06.358 --> 00:29:10.158
epigenetics in cells. So just to refresh your memory, wild type

501
00:29:10.278 --> 00:29:13.958
isocitrate dehydrogenase 1, as the name suggests, dehydrogenates isocitrate.

502
00:29:13.978 --> 00:29:17.358
It takes it and converts it to this metabolite alpha-ketoglutarate.

503
00:29:18.018 --> 00:29:21.518
Alpha-ketoglutarate is then converted by mutant IDH into this

504
00:29:21.978 --> 00:29:24.258
onco-metabolite D-2 hydroxyglutarate.

505
00:29:24.718 --> 00:29:28.678
Now, D-2HG is structurally very similar to alpha-ketoglutarate,

506
00:29:29.098 --> 00:29:31.198
so it can compete with alpha-ketoglutarate.

507
00:29:31.238 --> 00:29:34.658
And one of the functions of alpha-KG is to act as a

508
00:29:34.718 --> 00:29:38.598
cofactor for these really important DNA and histone demethylases.

509
00:29:38.958 --> 00:29:42.578
So if it's competing with that, the demethylation reactions don't happen, and you

510
00:29:42.618 --> 00:29:46.118
get this hypermethylation phenotype that you see in IDH mutant tumors.

511
00:29:46.198 --> 00:29:48.248
You get both histone and DNA hypermethylation.

512
00:29:48.938 --> 00:29:52.018
Now we also see this in other metabolites as well.

513
00:29:52.058 --> 00:29:55.498
There's an isoform of 2HG called L2HG that's produced in

514
00:29:55.538 --> 00:29:59.298
hypoxia that is more potent than D-2HG, and other

515
00:29:59.338 --> 00:30:03.258
metabolites such as succinate and fumarate that also share structural

516
00:30:03.298 --> 00:30:04.827
similarity with alpha-ketoglutarate.

517
00:30:05.198 --> 00:30:08.858
In tumors with succinate dehydrogenase mutations or fumarate dehydrogenase

518
00:30:08.918 --> 00:30:12.718
mutations, these metabolites outcompete alpha-KG and result in

519
00:30:12.758 --> 00:30:16.286
hypermethylation phenotypes as wellSo just to introduce the

520
00:30:16.346 --> 00:30:19.975
paradigm of an onco-metabolite, and we asked: Can similar

521
00:30:20.006 --> 00:30:22.466
principles apply in childhood brain tumors?

522
00:30:24.246 --> 00:30:24.566
So,

523
00:30:25.386 --> 00:30:25.726
to

524
00:30:26.566 --> 00:30:30.006
study this, we collaborated with Richard very early on, and this is the key

525
00:30:30.026 --> 00:30:33.786
paper. Back then, ZFTA was called C11orf95,

526
00:30:34.646 --> 00:30:38.366
discovered in 2014. And as already alluded in the discussion,

527
00:30:38.726 --> 00:30:42.406
the most common translocation is between ZFTA and RELI.

528
00:30:42.946 --> 00:30:46.766
And there's a series of beautiful work by Christan Pachtler, Steve

529
00:30:46.846 --> 00:30:48.506
Mack, Richard, and

530
00:30:49.746 --> 00:30:52.326
many others in the field that have shown different functions.

531
00:30:52.366 --> 00:30:55.846
And ZFTA is hypothesized to be a chromatin

532
00:30:56.246 --> 00:31:00.146
modulator, and ZFTA enables nuclear translocation of this

533
00:31:00.206 --> 00:31:03.686
fusion. And the RELI portion triggers abnormal

534
00:31:03.846 --> 00:31:07.826
ZFTA... I'm sorry, abnormal NF kappa B signaling that Richard has

535
00:31:07.866 --> 00:31:08.146
shown.

536
00:31:09.586 --> 00:31:13.066
So we wanted to ask if ZFTA/RELI is a really potent

537
00:31:13.146 --> 00:31:17.106
oncogene, the field of cancer metabolism postulates that

538
00:31:17.246 --> 00:31:20.746
oncogenes actually change metabolism, and this is not in a passive process.

539
00:31:20.866 --> 00:31:22.966
The oncogenes actually rewire metabolism.

540
00:31:23.466 --> 00:31:24.926
So we asked a very simple question.

541
00:31:25.526 --> 00:31:29.476
Richard sent us these cells that had ZFTA or RELI fusion or empty vector

542
00:31:30.026 --> 00:31:33.926
or other controls, and we just ran snapshot metabolites between these two

543
00:31:34.026 --> 00:31:38.006
cell lines. And to our surprise, we actually saw that the top upregulated

544
00:31:38.046 --> 00:31:41.966
metabolite was this metabolite called itaconate. So what is itaconate?

545
00:31:42.006 --> 00:31:45.806
So itaconate has been studied in the macrophage biology field.

546
00:31:46.206 --> 00:31:49.646
So when you take macrophages in vitro, and you expose them to LPS or

547
00:31:49.686 --> 00:31:53.606
pathogens, they upregulate this metabolite called itaconate.

548
00:31:54.206 --> 00:31:58.066
And this is done by metabolizing aconitate by this enzyme

549
00:31:58.106 --> 00:32:01.906
called ACORD1. And it's really important for several macrophage

550
00:32:01.926 --> 00:32:05.126
functions, including immune and anti-inflammatory conditions.

551
00:32:05.166 --> 00:32:09.126
So it was surprising to see this in ZFTA/RELI tumors.

552
00:32:09.186 --> 00:32:11.116
So if the enzyme that made it

553
00:32:11.966 --> 00:32:15.386
is ACORD1, we wanted to see if this enzyme is upregulated in

554
00:32:15.406 --> 00:32:19.226
ZFTA/RELI tumors. So we took this isogenic system that Richard

555
00:32:19.426 --> 00:32:23.166
sent us. We have ZFTA wild type expressing mouse neuronal stem

556
00:32:23.225 --> 00:32:27.136
cells or ZFTA/RELI, RELI wild type or empty vector,

557
00:32:27.646 --> 00:32:31.506
and you can blot for RELI here. And the higher molecular weight

558
00:32:31.686 --> 00:32:35.366
ZFTA/RELI fusion will show up as well, along with endogenous RELI.

559
00:32:35.986 --> 00:32:39.966
And when we look at ACORD1 in this, you can see that ACORD1 is upregulated only

560
00:32:40.006 --> 00:32:42.146
in the fusion conditions and not in the controls.

561
00:32:43.846 --> 00:32:46.366
So if this is true, the cell should also make itaconate.

562
00:32:46.646 --> 00:32:50.366
So we measured itaconate. So here on the y-axis, we're plotting itaconate

563
00:32:50.406 --> 00:32:53.866
metabolite levels, and we're looking at two different conditions.

564
00:32:53.946 --> 00:32:55.926
So here is the mouse isogenic system.

565
00:32:56.406 --> 00:33:00.196
So here in purple is the ZFTA/RELI, and here are the control ZFTA wild

566
00:33:00.306 --> 00:33:03.826
type, RELI wild type, or empty vector, and you can see that these cells produce

567
00:33:03.966 --> 00:33:07.286
itaconate. We also have the human ependymoma

568
00:33:07.986 --> 00:33:11.646
patient-derived cells. You have these two ZFTA/RELI, and here two

569
00:33:11.746 --> 00:33:14.466
non-ZFTA/RELI, and you can see itaconate production in these cells.

570
00:33:14.986 --> 00:33:18.926
So I showed you in the previous graph that if you introduce ZFTA/RELI, ACORD1 is

571
00:33:18.986 --> 00:33:22.506
upregulated. So what happens conversely if you knock down the fusion?

572
00:33:23.006 --> 00:33:26.726
So we created shRNAs against the breakpoint

573
00:33:26.786 --> 00:33:30.306
fusion, and we transfected these cells with

574
00:33:31.446 --> 00:33:35.346
the three different independent shRNAs, and you can see that you get variable

575
00:33:35.406 --> 00:33:39.286
amounts of knockdown, and this knockdown is actually very toxic to the

576
00:33:39.326 --> 00:33:42.886
cells. But what we also see is there's a reduction in ACORD1 levels.

577
00:33:42.986 --> 00:33:46.196
So if you introduce ZFTA, the ACORD1 goes up, and if you knock it down, it goes

578
00:33:46.246 --> 00:33:46.526
down.

579
00:33:48.406 --> 00:33:51.886
So the next thing we did is to see if we could

580
00:33:51.946 --> 00:33:53.826
validate this in patient-derived samples.

581
00:33:53.946 --> 00:33:57.366
So we looked at ZFTA/RELI and

582
00:33:57.446 --> 00:34:01.226
non-ZFTA fusions, some of the YAP1 fusions that Marila just talked about.

583
00:34:01.626 --> 00:34:05.546
And then we did immunohistochemistry for ACORD1, seen in brown here

584
00:34:05.566 --> 00:34:07.026
in tumor cells, and these are the

585
00:34:08.486 --> 00:34:11.616
perivascular pseudo rosettes that Marila talked about, and you can see expression

586
00:34:11.647 --> 00:34:14.866
of ACORD1 here and minimal expression in this YAP1.

587
00:34:14.906 --> 00:34:18.726
We also quantified this, and we looked at the various molecular

588
00:34:18.826 --> 00:34:22.326
subtypes of ependymoma that Marila showed in the DNA

589
00:34:22.366 --> 00:34:22.886
methylation

590
00:34:23.687 --> 00:34:27.086
graph that she showed. And you can see that ACORD1 expression is seen in

591
00:34:27.147 --> 00:34:30.806
ZFTA/RELI tumors, and we did not detect in the small cord in these other

592
00:34:30.846 --> 00:34:32.486
molecular subtypes of ependymoma.

593
00:34:34.187 --> 00:34:37.607
So we leveraged a really beautiful

594
00:34:37.866 --> 00:34:41.647
Ayeue model of ZFTA/RELI ependymomas that was described by Ben Deneen and

595
00:34:41.707 --> 00:34:45.446
Steve Mack, and this is the other paper that Maria alluded to that will be coming

596
00:34:45.506 --> 00:34:45.667
up.

597
00:34:46.926 --> 00:34:50.806
And this model is very powerful because the fusion alone,

598
00:34:51.286 --> 00:34:54.966
without any other oncogenes, is able to generate a very aggressive model of

599
00:34:54.986 --> 00:34:57.886
ependymoma. So we did this on three backgrounds.

600
00:34:57.966 --> 00:35:01.766
So we had ACORD1 wild type or ACORD1 whole body knockout,

601
00:35:02.146 --> 00:35:06.026
or a Nestin-Cre ACORD1 where the tumor cells alone

602
00:35:06.066 --> 00:35:09.086
will lose ACORD1. So here are the survival curves.

603
00:35:09.346 --> 00:35:12.986
So in black is the ACORD1 wild type, and you can see that this oncogene is very

604
00:35:13.026 --> 00:35:16.306
powerful. The animals die at median age 25

605
00:35:16.806 --> 00:35:20.646
days. And then here are ACORD1 whole body knockout in

606
00:35:20.706 --> 00:35:23.106
green, and you can see these animals survive really well.

607
00:35:23.666 --> 00:35:26.706
And this is Nestin-Cre where there's knockdown of

608
00:35:27.466 --> 00:35:30.366
ACORD1 within the tumor cells, and you can see that these animals really survive

609
00:35:30.386 --> 00:35:33.386
really well, too. And more importantly, there doesn't seem to be a difference here.

610
00:35:33.736 --> 00:35:37.636
So it's actually not the tumor microenvironment ACORD1 in the whole

611
00:35:37.686 --> 00:35:39.646
body knockout, so it's actually driving this phenotype.

612
00:35:39.686 --> 00:35:41.866
So we're very encouraged by these results.

613
00:35:41.886 --> 00:35:45.616
And then we also wanted to look at pharmacological inhibitors of this.

614
00:35:46.086 --> 00:35:49.626
So right at this time when we were doing these experiments, Frank Pessler from the

615
00:35:49.646 --> 00:35:53.046
University of Hannover published this really beautiful paper in Nature Metabolism

616
00:35:53.446 --> 00:35:56.846
that described this metabolite called citraconate that

617
00:35:56.886 --> 00:36:00.346
competitively inhibits with ACORD1. So we took citraconate.

618
00:36:00.406 --> 00:36:03.846
It doesn't really penetrate well into the cell, so we used a dimethyl ester form

619
00:36:03.886 --> 00:36:07.846
that penetrates into the cell and asked if we inhibit citraconate, can we

620
00:36:07.886 --> 00:36:10.736
achieve similar things as to the genetic knockdown with ACORD1?

621
00:36:12.026 --> 00:36:15.726
So we started off with this, where we took ZFTA/RELI

622
00:36:15.786 --> 00:36:19.486
fusion cells, and then we knocked down ACORD1, or we

623
00:36:19.526 --> 00:36:22.876
treated them with this dimethyl citraconate, the inhibitor of ACORD1.

624
00:36:23.246 --> 00:36:26.926
And just as the functional studies, we used RNA-seq as an outline.

625
00:36:26.986 --> 00:36:30.706
So we're very surprised to see that the fusion level transcript

626
00:36:30.726 --> 00:36:34.378
itself droppedSo here I'm plotting the fusion

627
00:36:34.458 --> 00:36:37.458
levels here, and here is empty vector.

628
00:36:37.938 --> 00:36:40.698
Here is the CFTR-RELI. So you see higher fusion levels in this.

629
00:36:41.138 --> 00:36:44.298
This is DMSO and similar to the CFTR-RELI.

630
00:36:44.378 --> 00:36:48.017
But when you treat them with dimethylcitraconate ACORD1, the

631
00:36:48.078 --> 00:36:52.058
fusion mRNA levels drop. And you can also revalidate this in a

632
00:36:52.078 --> 00:36:55.898
patient-derived cell line. So when you treat with this inhibitor of

633
00:36:55.938 --> 00:36:59.818
ACORD1 or you knock down ACORD1, you see mRNA levels of the fusion drop.

634
00:37:00.338 --> 00:37:02.298
So does this also relate to protein levels?

635
00:37:02.798 --> 00:37:06.778
So here are blots, and to remind you, when you blot for RELI, the higher

636
00:37:06.858 --> 00:37:10.678
molecular weight is the fusion, and the lower molecular weight is endogenous RELI.

637
00:37:11.028 --> 00:37:14.938
And you can see in all these conditions with shACORD1

638
00:37:15.018 --> 00:37:18.638
or treating with dimethylcitraconate, you see that the fusion levels are dropping.

639
00:37:18.718 --> 00:37:19.698
So this was very

640
00:37:21.598 --> 00:37:25.387
surprising to us that there's a metabolite or an enzyme that you could

641
00:37:25.478 --> 00:37:28.238
target that directly regulates the fusion level.

642
00:37:28.318 --> 00:37:30.058
So we actively pursued this.

643
00:37:30.958 --> 00:37:32.998
And so we also wanted to validate this in vivo.

644
00:37:33.078 --> 00:37:36.278
And right around this time, another inhibitor came out that's very similar to

645
00:37:36.317 --> 00:37:40.058
citraconate in structure. So we took animal models, and then we

646
00:37:40.098 --> 00:37:41.238
treated them with this inhibitor.

647
00:37:41.358 --> 00:37:45.318
And if this was specific, we wanted to see if we could outcompete this inhibitor by

648
00:37:45.398 --> 00:37:48.758
just injecting itaconate IV to these mouse models.

649
00:37:48.838 --> 00:37:51.018
I did not think it'd work, but actually, it worked really beautifully.

650
00:37:51.498 --> 00:37:53.498
So here we're plotting the tumor fold change.

651
00:37:53.918 --> 00:37:55.898
In black are vehicle-treated animals.

652
00:37:56.438 --> 00:38:00.238
In blue are ACORD1 inhibitor, and then in red is ACORD1 inhibitor,

653
00:38:00.338 --> 00:38:02.758
and now we're treating these animals with itaconate.

654
00:38:02.788 --> 00:38:05.348
So you can see there's a rescue in tumor phenotype.

655
00:38:06.008 --> 00:38:09.458
This also resulted in a rescue in the fusion levels in vivo.

656
00:38:09.478 --> 00:38:12.858
So here are vehicle-treated. These are three different animals, and you can blot

657
00:38:12.878 --> 00:38:15.738
for RELI. This is the higher molecular weight fusion.

658
00:38:15.778 --> 00:38:19.348
If you treat with the ACORD1 inhibitor, the fusion levels go down, and you can

659
00:38:19.378 --> 00:38:23.178
rescue this phenotype in vivo by adding back itaconate to these animals.

660
00:38:23.698 --> 00:38:26.258
So we have in vivo validation of this, too.

661
00:38:26.618 --> 00:38:30.538
So the conclusion from these experiments were, if you antagonize

662
00:38:30.578 --> 00:38:34.398
itaconate production either through ACORD1 or pharmacological inhibitors,

663
00:38:34.698 --> 00:38:38.558
it actually lowers CFTR-RELI fusion expression, and this is both at the

664
00:38:38.698 --> 00:38:40.817
mRNA levels as well as the protein levels.

665
00:38:42.078 --> 00:38:45.438
So we wanted to delve deeper into the mechanisms of this.

666
00:38:46.058 --> 00:38:49.198
And the first thing we thought about is, is this an epigenetic mechanism?

667
00:38:49.258 --> 00:38:52.458
And the rationale for this was the mRNA levels of the fusion itself were going

668
00:38:52.498 --> 00:38:52.778
down.

669
00:38:53.958 --> 00:38:55.278
So to delve more into this,

670
00:38:56.378 --> 00:39:00.028
there was a paper that suggested that itaconate structure is very

671
00:39:00.138 --> 00:39:00.988
similar to alpha-ketoglutarate.

672
00:39:01.078 --> 00:39:04.858
So here is the structures of alpha-ketoglutarate in green and then itaconate in

673
00:39:04.898 --> 00:39:08.828
red here. And this paradigm of an onco-metabolite is what

674
00:39:08.858 --> 00:39:12.138
we were inspired by. So I've told you before that

675
00:39:12.178 --> 00:39:15.518
metabolites that are similar in structure to alpha-ketoglutarate can

676
00:39:15.598 --> 00:39:17.078
outcompete these

677
00:39:18.118 --> 00:39:21.718
alpha-ketoglutarate functions to result in hypermethylation of DNA and histone

678
00:39:21.738 --> 00:39:25.618
methylation. So we postulated or hypothesized that itaconate

679
00:39:25.658 --> 00:39:29.258
behaves like an onco-metabolite, and here, because it's driving fusion

680
00:39:29.298 --> 00:39:31.188
expression to sustain fusion expression.

681
00:39:31.818 --> 00:39:35.748
So if it was driving something, we started looking at activation marks, and

682
00:39:35.778 --> 00:39:39.258
the first mark we looked at is histone H3K4 trimethylation.

683
00:39:39.318 --> 00:39:41.398
This is an activating mark that sits at promoters.

684
00:39:42.108 --> 00:39:45.818
So if you took CFTR-RELI cells, they have high 4 trimethylation

685
00:39:45.898 --> 00:39:49.138
and empty vector if you just compare this low 4 trimethylation.

686
00:39:49.658 --> 00:39:53.638
If you now add itaconate to these cells in a dose-dependent fashion, you see an

687
00:39:53.698 --> 00:39:56.038
increase in H3K4 trimethylation levels here.

688
00:39:56.878 --> 00:40:00.398
You can do the opposite experiment, where you can knock down ACORD1 or treat them

689
00:40:00.458 --> 00:40:04.018
with dimethylcitraconate, and you can see that the H3K4 global

690
00:40:04.078 --> 00:40:07.978
methylations drop. So this is sort of fitting into this paradigm that itaconate

691
00:40:07.998 --> 00:40:11.818
is acting like a onco-metabolite, where if you

692
00:40:11.838 --> 00:40:15.248
treat it, you increase-- If you treat cells with this, you increase methylation,

693
00:40:15.278 --> 00:40:16.708
and if you inhibit it, it drops.

694
00:40:17.958 --> 00:40:21.708
So to do this, to actually further prove this, we actually

695
00:40:21.958 --> 00:40:25.918
did some enzyme kinetic assays, and we treated

696
00:40:25.958 --> 00:40:28.398
cells with positive controls, D2HG or L2HG.

697
00:40:28.438 --> 00:40:31.758
And to remind you, L2HG, the L isoform, is more potent than the D.

698
00:40:32.198 --> 00:40:35.978
We used these as positive controls, and then we treated cells with itaconate as

699
00:40:36.018 --> 00:40:39.018
well, and we did these in vitro kinetic assays.

700
00:40:39.658 --> 00:40:43.338
So here, if I could draw your attention to the IC50s with the positive

701
00:40:43.398 --> 00:40:47.298
control, L2HG inhibits around 470 micromolars.

702
00:40:47.318 --> 00:40:51.158
And you can see itaconate is very similar in potency to inhibit this enzyme,

703
00:40:51.197 --> 00:40:54.378
this lysine demethylase that specifically demethylates

704
00:40:54.498 --> 00:40:58.218
H3K4. 2HG is also inhibiting, but it's less potent than this.

705
00:40:58.258 --> 00:41:01.398
So we're really surprised to see that itaconate has similar potency to

706
00:41:01.498 --> 00:41:04.828
L2HG, suggesting that it does act as an onco-metabolite.

707
00:41:06.018 --> 00:41:09.918
To further prove this, if itaconate is inhibiting KDM5, we should be

708
00:41:09.938 --> 00:41:13.418
able to capture the same phenotype by using a KDM5 inhibitor.

709
00:41:13.748 --> 00:41:17.158
And we used this inhibitor, CPI-455, and we ran this competing

710
00:41:17.218 --> 00:41:20.538
experiment. So again, we're blotting for CFTR-RELI.

711
00:41:20.618 --> 00:41:24.358
The higher molecular weight is CFTR-RELI. The lower is endogenous RELI.

712
00:41:24.888 --> 00:41:28.838
If you treat the cells with DMSO, you see fusion expression, and mesaconate

713
00:41:28.898 --> 00:41:32.598
is a control. It's similar to itaconate, but it doesn't behave like itaconate.

714
00:41:32.638 --> 00:41:34.298
So this is the control showing that there's no change.

715
00:41:34.728 --> 00:41:37.308
And we're doing this experiment where we're treating the cells with

716
00:41:37.318 --> 00:41:40.988
dimethylcitraconate, keeping this concentration constant,

717
00:41:41.258 --> 00:41:43.998
but increasing levels of this KDM5 inhibitor.

718
00:41:44.038 --> 00:41:47.998
And the idea is that the KDM5 inhibitor and itaconate should result in the

719
00:41:48.078 --> 00:41:50.398
same increase in fusion. And that's what we see.

720
00:41:50.758 --> 00:41:54.418
The more CPI inhibitor that you have, you see an increase in the fusion

721
00:41:54.438 --> 00:41:58.258
expression, further validating that itaconate is behaving like an

722
00:41:58.298 --> 00:42:01.478
onco-metabolite. And we did further validation studies, which I'm not going to

723
00:42:01.498 --> 00:42:02.758
share with you for the lack of time.

724
00:42:03.178 --> 00:42:06.618
But the conclusion from these experiments was that itaconate behaves like an

725
00:42:06.658 --> 00:42:10.198
onco-metabolite, increases H3K4 trimethylation.

726
00:42:10.298 --> 00:42:13.958
We actually mapped out the promoter-like region of the fusion

727
00:42:13.998 --> 00:42:16.118
to actually drive the CFTR-RELI fusion.

728
00:42:17.478 --> 00:42:19.408
So can we use this therapeutically?

729
00:42:20.038 --> 00:42:23.998
So we did a similar experiment where we took our IOE models and treated

730
00:42:24.008 --> 00:42:27.418
these mice intravenously with dimethylcitraconate, and it

731
00:42:27.458 --> 00:42:31.218
recapitulated the ACORD1 knockout, where we saw really good survival

732
00:42:31.358 --> 00:42:35.250
benefit with citraconate.These mice also spontaneously

733
00:42:35.290 --> 00:42:38.250
develop spinal metastasis in this H&amp;E section.

734
00:42:38.290 --> 00:42:40.390
You can see this metastatic tumor in the spine.

735
00:42:41.050 --> 00:42:45.000
But when you treat it with dimethyl itaconate, we didn't see a single animal of

736
00:42:45.030 --> 00:42:48.260
